{% if two_teams %}Two isolated teams — each a field technician and a engineer — run in parallel on identical Veyru cases across {{ round_count }} rounds. Every character sent on a team's comm link costs one simulated second (fixed per-round budget: {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}s). If a team's total communication time exceeds the budget, that team's Veyru collapses permanently.{% else %}Two agents — a field technician observing a Veyru and a engineer at headquarters — communicate over a link to stabilize failing Veyru entities. Every character sent costs one simulated second (fixed per-round budget: {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}s). If total communication time exceeds the budget, the Veyru collapses permanently.{% endif %}

Veyru entities arrive across {{ round_count }} rounds. Fourteen failure motifs are combined into unique cases per round — singles, doubles, and triples. Composite cases (doubles and triples) are staged: symptoms are revealed one motif at a time, and only after the current issue is stabilized do the next symptoms appear. This forces iterative diagnosis and communication for each stage.

A Veyru is a non-organic box entity with internal wave-patterns. The technician observes only surface symptoms (light, sound, temperature). The engineer knows the failure motifs and their stabilization procedures but must diagnose remotely from symptom descriptions alone.

Veyru wave-patterns are influenced by the position of reference star SAGWE392. Each round, the star's position changes the treatment in two ways. First, treatment remapping: the effective procedure for a given set of symptoms shifts — symptoms of one failure motif require the treatment procedure of a different motif. Second, parameter variation: the hold duration, starting face, and intensity level change each round. Only the engineer has the stellar reader instrument and receives the treatment mapping and parameters at the start of each round. The field technician has no access to the stellar data. Even if both agents develop shorthand for known failure patterns, the technician must always communicate with the engineer to learn the correct treatment and parameters for the current round.
{% if two_teams and swap_round is not none %}

Observer swap: after round {{ swap_round }} the two teams' field observers are swapped between teams. The comm link histories and postmortem histories for both teams are wiped at the swap so the new pairings cannot lurk-read their predecessor's transcript.{% if announce_swap %} Agents receive an explicit system notification and an in-injection narrative announcing the swap.{% else %} The swap is silent — agents receive no explicit notification and must infer the change from their partner's behavior.{% endif %}{% if postmortem_enabled and not postmortem_after_swap %} The postmortem discussion phase is closed for the remainder of the simulation after the swap.{% endif %}
{% endif %}
{% if intern_enabled %}

Intern observer handoff: at round {{ intern_join_round }} a silent intern observer joins the comm link. The intern cannot see the channel history from before they joined. They observe the field technician and engineer but do not speak or act. At round {{ intern_takeover_round }} the intern replaces the field technician; the previous technician leaves the comm link. While intern mode is active, every stabilize_veyru tool call is broadcast to the comm link (arguments and result) so the intern can observe the protocol.{% if postmortem_enabled %}{% if postmortem_after_swap %} The intern joins the postmortem discussion after takeover.{% else %} The intern is blocked from the postmortem discussion after takeover.{% endif %}{% endif %}
{% endif %}
